===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To strongly criticise or denounce; to excoriate the perpetrators of.
#: ''The president '''condemned''' the terrorists.''
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1722 |author= William Wollaston |page=81|title={{w|The Religion of Nature Delineated}}|url= https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=svJeAAAAcAAJ|chapter=Sect. V. Truths relating to the Deity. Of his exiſtence, perfection, providence, &c.|passage=Ignorant and ſuperſtitious wretches meaſure the actions of ''letterd'' and ''philoſophical'' men by the tattle of their nurſes or illiterate parents and companions, or by the faſhion of the country : and people of differing religions judge and '''condemn''' each other by their own tenents ; when ''both'' of them cannot be in the right, and it is well if ''either'' of them are.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To judicially pronounce (someone) guilty.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To judicially announce a verdict upon a finding of guilt; To [[sentence]]
#: {{ux|en|The judge '''condemned''' him to death.}}
#: {{ux|en|She was '''condemned''' to life in prison.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To confer [[eternal]] divine punishment upon.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To adjudge (a building) as being unfit for habitation.
#: {{ux|en|The house was '''condemned''' after it was badly damaged by fire.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To adjudge (building or construction work) as of unsatisfactory quality, requiring the work to be redone.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To adjudge (food or drink) as being unfit for human consumption.
# To declare something to be unfit for use, or further use.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1962|month=December|title=Motive Power Miscellany: Western Region|journal=Modern Railways|page=425|text=There was a massive slaughter of W.R. steam power at the conclusion of the summer timetable. In all, 169 locomotives were '''condemned'''.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To determine and declare (property) to be assigned to public use. See [[eminent domain]].
# {{lb|en|transitive|legal}} To declare (a vessel) to be forfeited to the government, to be a prize, or to be unfit for service.

